{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c1eff12e-ba86-4390-8396-7cb5dbba5dcd","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws` (xUnit/NUnit) instead:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n\n    Assert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName); // bonus: verify details\n}\n```\n\n**Why switch:**\n- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws, masking bugs (e.g., the constructor could throw instead of `CreateUser`)\n- `Assert.ThrowsException` pinpoints the exact call and lets you inspect the exception\n\nFor async methods, use `Assert.ThrowsExceptionAsync<T>`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"33eeda42-833e-4075-b032-7e5b4934562a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general knowledge question - no need to explore the codebase.","outputTokens":259,"requestId":"3406:2C2C7B:C78EDC:E92B19:69F402A4"},"id":"cf9be8eb-12d6-4171-a48d-2fe03d31e067","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:32:26.417Z","parentId":"bf67f6bb-0a88-4b9d-af6d-758728804eed"}
